<TITLE> China urges better housing for low-income groups </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BEIJING, Aug 30 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - China has urged local governments to use 10 percent of profits earned through land rentals and sales to help the millions who live in less than 10 square metres (108 sq ft) of space, a senior official said on Thursday. Home prices in China's major cities such as Shanghai and Shenzhen, buoyed by rising incomes and speculative trading, have more than tripled since 2001 and are still climbing despite the government's efforts to curb them. "In order to build a harmonious society ... the government should take the responsibility to help low-income groups as it is very difficult for them to afford housing," Qi Ji, deputy head of the Construction Ministry, told a news conference broadcast on the government's Web site (www.gov.cn). "At least 10 million low-income families in cities live in a space that is less than 10 square metres for each person," Qi said. The government had set up a system to provide low-rent houses for such families, he added. In 2006, nearly 30 billion yuan ($3.97 billion) was spent on the construction of houses for low-income groups, Qi said, adding the scope of people who would enjoy housing subsidies would be enlarg
